Alternatively, perhaps the input is given as each string on its own line, so we can read each with a read statement. Wait, the first Java program's code:

for (int i = 0; i < num; i++) {
    String s = sc.next();
    arr.add(s);
}

So sc.next() reads the next token, so each string is a token separated by whitespace. So the input for the first program is the number followed by num tokens (each possibly containing letters, but the code is looking for 'C's). So in Fortran, to read the same input, we can read the first integer, then read num strings, each as a character array of length, say, up to some maximum. But in the code, the strings are stored in an ArrayList, so each can be of varying length, but in the code, when accessing arr.get(k).charAt(i), it's assuming that each string is at least length num?
